        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText> We will observe CO(3-2) emission and dust thermal emission from a star-forming galaxy at z=1.4515. Since we already have CO(5-4) map in band 6 and the dust thermal emission map in the band obtained with ALMA, we calculate the on-source time based on the results.

Expected CO(3-2) emission line:
 The emission line ratio between CO(5-4) and CO(3-2) is assumed to be Sν(5−4)/Sν(3−2)=2. This is the cases for color selected galaxies such as sBzK galaxies at z~1.5 or M82 (Carilli and Walter 2013, ARAA 51, 105). We assume the intrinsic size of molecular gas clouds is 0.5” from the CO(5-4) map. Considering the difference of beam-size in CO(5-4) observations (~0.75”) and proposed CO(3-2) observations (0.3”), we calculated the signal-to-noise ratio (S/N) for an extended (i.e., ~0.5”) cloud. It is also assumed that each cloud has a Gaussian distribution convolved with round beam-size for simplicity. Then if a noise per beam in CO(3-2) observations (σ32) is 0.29 times that in CO(5-4) observations (σ54), the same SN is obtained as that in the map shown in Figure 1 of Scientific justification, provided that the line ratio between Sν(3-2) and Sν(5-4) is constant in the galaxy.  Since the SN in CO(5-4) is not so good, to achieve the objectives in this observation more accurately, we aim to improve the SN two times as compared with that in CO(5-4).  Since the σ54 is 1 mJy/beam in 50 km/s bin (Figure 1),  σ32 should be 0.14 mJy/beam.  According to the sensitivity calculator, the on-source time of 3.5 hours can attain this level.

Expected dust thermal emission:
 The dust thermal emission is expected to be 0.2 mJy in this band from the SED in FIR. With this on-source time (3.5 hours), the noise in 6.56 GHz band is 0.008 mJy/beam and the SN is ~25.  With this SN, we expect we will be able to see the distribution of dust thermal emission. 
Including overheads, the total observing time from OT is 7.54 hours.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
