    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Elliptical galaxies are considered to be formed through merging. We have recently found a star-forming galaxy at z=1.4 showing the presence of multi-component molecular gas clouds in CO(5-4) emission line with ALMA. It is a main sequence galaxy at z=1.4 and a stellar mass of the galaxy is ~2x10^11 Msun. The rest-frame optical surface brightness distribution with WFC3/HST shows a smooth profile described by Sersic index of 7~8 and a half light radius of ~8 kpc. In addition, a rest-UV image taken with ACS/HST shows the presence of two star-forming regions in the galaxy. The galaxy is probably in a forming (or major evolution) phase of a present-day elliptical galaxy. We see not only the molecular gas clouds, but also the stellar component as well as star-forming regions in the galaxy. It gives us a unique opportunity to dissect evolution process of a galaxy. To unveil the process of elliptical formation, we aim to examine the locations in the galaxy, sizes, gas density, dust mass, and gas-dust ratio, etc of the molecular clouds with CO(3-2) observations at a higher angular resolution.</prp:abstract>
